### Describing Rectilinear Motion using Equations (for uniform acceleration)

#### 2.4.1 Derivation of the Equations of Motion (for uniform acceleration)

In this section, we will analyse the motion for an object moving in a straight line with **uniform acceleration** and derive equations that could be used for similar motions with uniform acceleration.

Suppose at time = 0, the object is at point O with an initial velocity of \(u\). The object moves at uniform acceleration of \(a\) until time = \(t\), and has travelled through a displacement of \(s\) to arrive at point A with the final velocity of \(v\).

Let us look at its velocity-time graph:

Note: acceleration of object, \(a\) is given by the gradient of its \(v\) - \(t\) graph,

\[a=\frac{v-u}{t}\]

\[v=u+a\ t\]

Note: The displacement of object from point O, \(s\), is given by the area under its \(v\) - \(t\) graph from time = \(0\) to time = \(t\),

\[s=\frac{1}{2}\left(u+v\right)t\]

Substitute Eqn (1) into (2), we have

\[s=\frac{1}{2}\left[u+\left(u+a\ t\right)\right]t\]

\[s=u\ t+\frac{1}{2}\ a\ t^{2}\]

From Eqn (1), we have

\[t=\frac{v-u}{a}\ \ \text{ and substitute into Eqn (2), we have}\]

\[s=\frac{1}{2}\left(u+v\right)\left(\frac{v-u}{a}\right)\]

\[\Rightarrow\]

\[\nu^{2}=u^{2}+2\ a\ s\]

**Note:**

* The equation \(s=u\ t+\frac{1}{2}\ a\ t^{2}\) sets the reference point \(s=0\) at \(t=0\).
* The "boxed" equations can only be used if **the acceleration is constant**.
* The equations are **vector equations.** Therefore, variables have to be analysed along the same dimension. For example, if we choose to analyse the motion along the \(x\)-direction, then we can only use quantities like \(u_{x}\)\(v_{x}\) and \(a_{x}\). Acceleration along the \(y\)-direction \(a_{y}\) will not affect motion along the \(x\)-direction.

