### The Integral: \(\int y\ dx\)

The reverse process to taking the derivative is referred to either as _integration_ or finding the _anti-derivative_. Graphically, it is equivalent to finding the area under the curve. Let us see why.

Consider a \(y\)-\(x\) graph as shown in Figure 3. Suppose we wish to find the area under the graph from some initial \(x\) value, \(x_{\text{initial}}\) to some final \(x\) value, \(x_{\text{final}}\). One way to do so is break the area up into \(n\) number of small rectangles each of some area, \(A_{i}\).

Hence, the area of each small rectangle can be written as: \(A_{i}=y_{i}\Delta x\) and the total area under the curve can be estimated by summing the area of all these little rectangles, i.e.

\[\text{Total area, }A=\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_{i}\Delta x\]

where the symbol \(\sum\) (upper case Greek sigma) signifies a sum over all terms, i.e. over all values of \(i\).

For the approximation of the area to be even better, we can try to divide the area into smaller and smaller rectangles, by decrease the interval \(\Delta x\), i.e. we say that we let \(\Delta x\to 0\). Therefore,

\[A=\lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\sum_{i=1}^{n}y_{i}\Delta x\]

This is also written as \(\int\limits_{x_{\text{final}}}^{x_{\text{final}}}y(x)\ dx\). So, \(\int\limits_{x_{\text{final}}}^{x_{\text{final}}}y(x)\ dx\) is the area under the \(y\)-\(x\) graph.

